bug.short_desc: [compiler] NPE in ImplicitNullAnnotationVerifier.collectOverriddenMethods from Content Assist in a .jpage file

long_desc.thetext:
Create in a root of a project a new file called jots.jpage and paste the following in it: String s = "foo"; s.
On the line "s." press Ctrl+Space. This causes an NPE to be logged. I am using fairly recent BETA_JAVA8 plugins and it's possible this might have been fixed in the latest. I'll test this again once I'm up-to-date.

Timo, I could not reproduce the NPE with the latest code.
I will list down the steps:
1) Create a New project test. 2) Switch on the null annotation settings and set null analysis as true.
If we look at the call stack, there is a call to the method: org.eclipse.jdt.internal.compiler.lookup.SourceTypeBinding.createArgumentBindings(SourceTypeBinding.java:2004)
This is under the compiler option: if (compilerOptions.isAnnotationBasedNullAnalysisEnabled) {
3) Create a file : jots.jpage (although , this should not matter, one could create a java file as well).
The presence of org.eclipse.jdt.internal.compiler.lookup.SourceTypeBinding.createArgumentBindings(SourceTypeBinding.java:2004)
suggests the test case may have something to with a function called with arguments.
Looking at the top of the stack: org.eclipse.jdt.internal.compiler.lookup.ImplicitNullAnnotationVerifier.collectOverriddenMethods(ImplicitNullAnnotationVerifier.java:190)
MethodBinding [] ifcMethods = superType.getMethods(selector, suggestedParameterLength);
A check
if (superType == null) return;
could be a temporary fix.
Thanks

Created attachment 240931 Workspace setup to show the NPE
I couldn't reproduce it in a fresh workspace either with latest BETA_JAVA8 enabled Eclipse buildId=4.4.0.Y20140315-2100 but after turning on all compiler warnings I got it happening reliably. Steps I took:
1) Start Eclipse with Java 8 EA JVM. 2) Create a new Java project, only set its name and confirm. 3) Right-click the name of the new project, select to create an unspecified new file and give it name jots.jpage . 4) Right-click the project, select properties and open Java compiler warnings page, then change options that match filters as follows: 4.1) Type filter ~ignore and change every option to Warning 4.2) Type filter ~off and turn on these options: Signal even if 'default'..., Include constructor or setter..., Signal use of deprecated..., Signal overriding or..., Include 'assert' in null..., Enable annotation-based..., Inherit null annotations and Enable syntactic... 4.3) Finally change Missing '@NonNullByDefault' annotation on package to Warning and click OK. 5) Type into the empty jots.jpage file: String s = "foo"; s. 6) Display Error log view from Window - Show View and the exception has been logged.
I've attached a copy of the workspace where only step 5 is needed to reproduce the NPE. I verified that the workspace continued to reproduce the NPE on next start after the ZIP was made.

org.eclipse.jdt.core.compiler.annotation.inheritNullAnnotations=enabled org.eclipse.jdt.core.compiler.annotation.nullanalysis=enabled

Created attachment 240947 Patch
Following are the steps the problem can be reproduced.
1) Start of eclipse instance and in the installed list of JRE's add 1.8 JRE. Make it default.
2) Create a new project.
3) Add a scrapbookpage to the project.
4) Add the following two options to the preferences file of the project: org.eclipse.jdt.core.compiler.annotation.inheritNullAnnotations=enabled org.eclipse.jdt.core.compiler.annotation.nullanalysis=enabled
5) Add the following lines in the scrapbook entry: String s = "foo"; s.| Press Ctrl + Space.
The patch solves the issue. I don't have a automated test case.
Thanks

Patch is good.
Two remarks still:
- we have two calls into findAllOverriddenMethods() so maybe doing the null check inside that method is more effective than doing it every time before calling.
- the root cause is a binary type, that is *not* j.l.Object, still its superclass is null. Is that expected? Is that specific to code snippets?

(In reply to Stephan Herrmann from comment #8) > - we have two calls into findAllOverriddenMethods() so maybe doing the null > check inside that method is more effective than doing it every time before > calling. >
findAllOverriddenMethods has two callers: 1. checkImplicitNullAnnotations(MethodBinding, AbstractMethodDeclaration, boolean, Scope) 2. collectOverriddenMethods(MethodBinding, char[], int, ReferenceBinding, Set, List) Calls findAllOverriddenMethods again and there are no other callers for collectOverriddenMethods.
> > - the root cause is a binary type, that is *not* j.l.Object, still its > superclass is null. Is that expected? Is that specific to code snippets?
I could not reproduce the error with a java project. It was specific to code snippets. I will update the bug as to why it only happens with code snippets.
Thanks

(In reply to shankha banerjee from comment #9) > (In reply to Stephan Herrmann from comment #8)
> > - the root cause is a binary type, that is *not* j.l.Object, still its > > superclass is null. Is that expected? Is that specific to code snippets? > > I could not reproduce the error with a java project. > It was specific to code snippets. > I will update the bug as to why it only happens with code snippets. > >
You are correct. The binary type (BinaryTypeBinding) superlclass does not point to java.lang.object. The NPE is specific to code snippets.
In case of JavaProject For a SourceTypeBinding, the function: ClassScope#connectSuperclass is called.
This sets the superClass to java.lang.Object (j.l.O).
-> sourceType.setSuperClass(getJavaLangObject());
so e.g -- Y.java -- class Y {}
In the class file Y.class the information is stored that Y inherits from j.l.O. When you refer Y in another class the BinaryTypeBinding (BTB) is created for Y and the following function: BinaryTypeBinding#cachePartsFrom is called. This sets the superclass of BTB to j.l.o.
This one has no target set. Is this going in for Luna?

(In reply to Jayaprakash Arthanareeswaran from comment #12) > This one has no target set. Is this going in for Luna?
Yes, Stephan, if you are all done with the review, please release, TIA.

(In reply to shankha banerjee from comment #11) > You are correct. The binary type (BinaryTypeBinding) superlclass does not > point to java.lang.object. The NPE is specific to code snippets. > > In case of JavaProject > For a SourceTypeBinding, the function: > ClassScope#connectSuperclass is called. > > This sets the superClass to java.lang.Object (j.l.O). > > -> sourceType.setSuperClass(getJavaLangObject()); > > so e.g > -- Y.java -- > class Y {} > > In the class file Y.class the information is stored that Y inherits from > j.l.O. > When you refer Y in another class the BinaryTypeBinding (BTB) is created for > Y and the following function: > BinaryTypeBinding#cachePartsFrom is called. > This sets the superclass of BTB to j.l.o.
Thanks, this explains why normally we never see a null superclass in classes other the j.l.O. Can you also say a word, why this situation is possible during eval? Is that part expected, or would that hint at a bug in the eval engine?

(In reply to Stephan Herrmann from comment #14) > Can you also say a word, why this situation is possible > during eval? Is that part expected, or would that hint at a bug in the eval > engine?
Hi Stephan, The information that top most class has a super class j.l.o is used in many places: ClassScope.java#detectHierarchyCycle.
To me it does not look like it is a bug at evaluation engine. There are checks in function such as
ClassScope.java#detectHierarchyCycle: 1189: if (parentType != null) {
When you say "a bug in eval engine ?", are you trying to suggest that we could also assign superClass of SourceTypeBinding to j.l.o ?
Thanks

Neither of the two remarks from comment 8 has been taking to conclusion:
(In reply to Stephan Herrmann from comment #8) > Patch is good. > > Two remarks still: > > - we have two calls into findAllOverriddenMethods() so maybe doing the null > check inside that method is more effective than doing it every time before > calling.
The patch still only protects one out of two callers, which only reduces the danger by 50% instead of eliminating it.
=> I'm moving the check into findAllOverriddenMethods() where it is now directly co-located with "currentType.id == TypeIds.T_JavaLangObject", which should also help to better understand the picture next time around.
> - the root cause is a binary type, that is *not* j.l.Object, still its > superclass is null. Is that expected? Is that specific to code snippets?
It hasn't been answered *why* indeed we have a null superclass. It would be super cool if we could tighten the rules so that only j.l.Object ever has a null superclass. Regarding eval: the real culprit is:
org.eclipse.jdt.internal.eval.CodeSnippetSkeleton.getSuperclassName()
which returns null and has been doing this since day 1.
I checked that changing this to returning "java/lang/Object" also fixes the NPE in this bug, but since I'm less certain regarding changes in eval, I'll leave this for a future investigation.

My fix comes separately via commit http://git.eclipse.org/c/jdt/eclipse.jdt.core.git/commit/?id=83a8a3171c136f3d1c745fbc6bc7fb39eeacdff1
